The Telegraph - Calcutta : International

 World Briefs

 Pope in Muslim U-turn 

 Vatican City, May 28 (Reuters): In a surprising about-face, Pope Benedict has decided to restore power and prestige to the Vatican department that oversees dialogue with Islam. 

 The departments return to its former status occurred as Catholic-Muslim dialogue is still suffering the negative effects of Benedicts speech last September in which he appeared to equate Islam with violence. 

 Afghan toll 

 Mazar-i-Sharif (Reuters): Thirteen people were killed in Afghanistan on Monday when police opened fire to break up a protest, witnesses said. 

 Wolfowitz 

 London (AP): Departing World Bank president Paul Wolfowitz on Monday blamed an overheated atmosphere in the media for forcing him to resign. 

 UK alcohol 

 London (AP): Bottles and cans of alcoholic drinks in Britain will carry health warnings on their labels next year. 

 Everest litter 

 Kathmandu (Reuters): Climbers from Japan and Nepal picked up 500 kg of tins, old tents, food and medicines littered on Mount Everest. 




